Difference b/n git clone and git fork.
-Clone-Make a local copy of a repository.
-Fork-Create your own server-side copy of someone else's repository, then clone your fork locally.

When would you use Fork instead of Clone?

I use a fork when I need my own copy of a repository, especially when contributing to open-source projects where I don't have write access. After forking, I clone my fork locally, make changes, and create a pull request back to the original repository.

Ex:1. Contributing to an Open-Source Project

Scenario 1: You want to fix a bug in Kubernetes, React, or VS Code.

✅ Use Fork

Original Repo (Microsoft/vscode)
        |
       Fork
        |
Your Repo (Suma/vscode)
        |
      Clone
        |
   Local Machine

Why?

You don't have write access to Microsoft's repo.
Fork creates your own repository on GitHub.
You make changes and raise a Pull Request (PR).

2.Contributing to someone else's repository

You don't have write permission
Maintaining your own customized version of an open-source project

When would you use Clone instead of Fork?

I use clone when I already have access to the repository or only need a local copy for development, deployment, learning, or backup purposes. Most internal company projects use clone rather than fork.

Ex 1.Working on Your Company's Repository

Scenario: You are a Desktop Engineering team member and have access to the company's Git repository.

✅ Use Clone

git clone https://github.com/company/intune-scripts.git
Show more lines

Why?

You already have write permissions.
No need for a separate repository.

Ex 2.Downloading Source Code for Learning

Scenario: You want to study the Linux source code.

✅ Use Clone

Reason:

You're only reading the code.
No intention to contribute.

Ex 3.Joining an Existing Internal Project

Scenario: Another engineer asks you to work on a project.

✅ Use Clone

Reason:

Team members collaborate directly on the same repository.
